ch shows that because Hawai`i’s kingdoms were established relatively recently, they could be observed and recorded by Cook and other European voyagers. Substantive and provocative, this book makes a major contribution to the literature of precontact Hawai`i and illuminates Hawai`i’s importance in the global theory and literature about divine kingship, archaic states, and sociopolitical evolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChiefdomszHawaiixHistory. 0aFirst contact (Anthropology)zHawaii. 0aFirst contact of aboriginal peoples with WesternerszHawaii. 0aHawaiiansxKings and rulers. 0aHawaiiansxPolitics and government. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aancient hawaii.  aancient history.  aanthropology.  aarchaeological record.  aarchaeology.  aarchaic states.  acaptain cook.  achiefdom.  acultural social.  adivine kingship.  aeuropean voyagers.  aglobal theory.  ahawaiian archipelago.  ahawaiian politics.  ahistorical anthropology.  ahistorical.  aisland life.  akings.  aleadership roles.  alinguistics.  anonfiction.  apolitics.  apolities.  apower struggle.  aprecontact hawaii.  aresearch.  asocial science.  asociopolitical evolution.  atheoretical perspective.  atraditional history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026725140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094784940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947849423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947849/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY